06913nam a22009375i 9789048544400DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021ne     fo  d z      eng d  a9789048544400  a(DE-B1597)576205  a(OCoLC)1249550783  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aBUS0430002bisacsh00aBranding Books Across the Ages :bStrategies and Key Concepts in Literary Branding /ced. by Helleke Braber, Maarten Steenmeijer, Jos Joosten, Jeroen Dera. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2021  a1 online resource (372 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tCultural Branding in the Early Modern Period -- tTelling a Double Story -- tA Hero and His History -- tFrom Immorality to Immortality -- tAllegories of Branding -- tBranding or Excluding? -- tHugo Claus -- tOne Book's Brand is Another Book's Frame -- t'The Most Successful Writer of the Netherlands' -- tYoung Adults as Branded Readers -- tOf Dust and Dollars -- t'This Is What We Share' -- tThe One Unforgivable Transgression? -- tBranding the Open-minded Nation -- tAgainst the Grain -- tIn Search of the Most Effective Way of Branding -- tIndex of Names0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aAs marketing specialists know all too well, our experience of products is prefigured by brands: trademarks that identify a product and differentiate it from its competitors. This process of branding has hitherto gained little academic discussion in the field of literary studies. Literary authors and the texts they produce, though, are constantly 'branded': from the early modern period onwards, they have been both the object and the initiator of a complex marketing process. This book analyzes this branding process throughout the centuries, focusing on the case of the Netherlands. To what extent is our experience of Dutch literature prefigured by brands, and what role does branding play when introducing European authors in the Dutch literary field (or vice versa)? By answering these questions, the volume seeks to show how literary scholars can account for the phenomenon of branding.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBooksxMarketingxHistory. 0aBranding (Marketing)xHistory. 0aPublishers and publishingxHistory. 4aContemporary History. 4aDutch and The Netherlands. 4aLanguage and Literature. 4aLiterary Theory, Criticism, and History. 4aModern History. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Marketing / General.2bisacsh  aBranding, Literary Studies, Literary Institutions, Translation Studies, Reception Studies.1 aAckermans, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBax, Sander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraber, Helleke van den, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraber, Helleke, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDebergh, Gwennie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeinsen, Lieke van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDera, Jeroen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDera, Jeroen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFranssen, Gaston, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeerdink, Nina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHam, Laurens, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHulsenboom, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id